brain-point-hint.content: It's great that you asked for a hint to help you solve the level.
Sometimes we need a hint when we are stuck.

brain-point-magnifyingGlassCuriosity.content: Good for you!  You are curious and like to learn.

brain-point-minorModification.content: You experimented by making a single change and

brain-point-unfinishedLevelReturn.content: You stuck with it and showed determination

brain-point-uniqueAttempts.content: You worked hard by trying to solve this level many different ways.

brain-point-uniquePartCombinations.content: You learned something about this problem by trying something new.

clear-all-0.content: If you ever get stuck, sometimes it's good to start fresh.
Hit the red "recycle button" to clear away all of the pieces.

clear-all-1.content: If you want to clean up the construction, and start over,
you can hit the red "recycle button" to clear away all of the pieces.

hint-battery-dead-0.content: Looks like your batteries are all used up.

hint-battery-dead-1.content: Uh oh.  We're all out of power.  Can you make it the rest of the way?

hint-breaking-0.content: Oops.  A part of your rover broke.
Breaks can happen when the rover goes too fast
when it hits the ground or goes over bumps.

hint-breaking-1.content: Was the rover going too fast, or was the design not sturdy enough?

hint-breaking-2.content: Do we need to redesign the rover to make it sturdier?

hint-breaking-3.content: Hmm..  How could we change the shape of the rover so that it doesn't break?

hint-breaking-4.content: Oops.  Do you think there are parts on the rover
we can move to prevent it from breaking?

hint-broke-wheel-0.content: Whoopsie.  There goes one of our wheels.
That can happen sometimes if a rover is too heavy, or we hit the ground too hard.

hint-broke-wheel-1.content: Do you think we put too much weight on it?

hint-broke-wheel-2.content: Oops!  I hope we didn't need that wheel.
Do you think we put too much weight on it?

hint-button-0-alt.content: The first thing I'd recommend is to review the course,
and see what obstacles the rover will need to overcome.

hint-button-0.content: One key to making a good rover is to look at the course
and think about the obstacles in your way.
Why don't you try that now?

hint-button-1-alt.content: What would you think if we put a piece here?

hint-button-1.content: Hmm... I think adding pieces here would help.

hint-button-2-alt.content: Let's add pieces here.  How does that look?

hint-button-2.content: What if we add some parts here?
Are there more pieces that need to be added?

hint-button-3-alt.content: Hmm.. I think adding these pieces would work.
What do you think of the design?

hint-button-3.content: Ahh..  How about adding these parts here?

hint-button-max-alt.content: That's all the ideas I've got.
You can try creating my design or create one of your own.

hint-button-max.content: That's all the help I can offer.
You can follow my design or come up with your own.

hint-button.content: Need some help?  Press the "hint button"
to get some tips on how to construct the rover.

hint-cannot-drag.content: Oops!  Can't drag that.  You can only move the blinking pieces.

hint-cannot-place-0.content: Oops.  Watch the color of the piece to see where it can be placed.
No pieces can be placed outside the dotted line.

hint-cannot-place-1.content: Oops.  You can't place that there.
Watch your piece's color to find out where it can and cannot be placed.

hint-course.content: Remember, you can use the orange square button
to review the course and get some ideas for how to build your rover.

hint-found-sunny-spot-0.content: We can recharge our batteries here using a solar panel.

hint-found-sunny-spot-1.content: This is a great spot to recharge our batteries with a solar panel.

hint-found-sunny-spot-2.content: This is a good place to stop and recharge your batteries with a solar panel.

hint-group-move.content: You can move a group of connected pieces by tapping and holding on a piece.
When the connected piece is highlighted, you can move the whole group.

hint-play.content: When you're ready to test out your rover, press the "play button."

hint-redo-0.content: Hmm... Are you stuck?  You can always reset and try again.

hint-redo-1.content: Press the "reset button" to redesign your rover and try again.

hint-redo-2.content: you can press the "reset button" to redesign your rover and try again.

hint-redo-3.content: You can always reset and redesign the rover.

hint-remove.content: If you want to remove a piece, drag it back
to the toolbox or outside the construction area.

hint-rocket-dead-0.content: Uh!  Your rockets are all used up.

hint-rocket-dead-1.content: Your rockets are out of fuel.

hint-rocket-dead-2.content: Can we make it the rest of the way without them?

hint-save.content: Want to save your rover to show your family and friends later?
You can access your saved rover's from the title screen.

hint-toolbox.content: To add pieces to your rover, drag them from the toolbox to your rover.

journal-full.content: Choose a picture that you don't want to keep,
and your new picture will replace it.

journal-none.content: You haven't saved a rover yet.
Next time you're creating a rover,
tap Sunspot's tablet in the bottom left corner
to take a picture of your rover, and it will be saved here.

journal-some.content: Tap on a picture to see one of your saved rovers.

journal-trash.content: Choose a picture to throw away.

level-prompt.content: Select the level you'd like to play.

level-win-1.content: Nice work.  Sunspot made it to the finish!

level-win-2.content: Good designing.  We made it to the goal!

level-win-4.content: You've made it!  Keep up the good work.

level-win-5.content: Good work.  That was a great design!

levels-complete.content: Excelsior!  You're a real rover constructor.
You've made rovers for all kinds of environments.
Have you collected the star in each level?
And don't forget to earn all of the badges!

lost-pieces-ok-0.content: but that's okay if we can still reach the goal.
If not, you can always reset.

lost-pieces-ok-1.content: That's okay, as long as we can still reach the goal.

mag-battery.content: Batteries store energy that we can use to power things like rovers.

mag-block.content: Wood and metal are useful materials for building.
We build all kinds of things out of them,
from boats, to houses, to rovers.

mag-cockpit.content: A cockpit is where the pilot of a vehicle sits.
It's built to keep them safe and enable them to control the vehicle.

mag-dust-storm.content: Dust storms occur when wind picks up the topsoil of an area and carries it along.

mag-finish-line.content: Finish line marks are at the end of a course,
and it's always fun to celebrate when you cross one.

mag-ice.content: Ice is formed when water gets really cold

mag-nose-cone.content: A nose cone generally appears on the front of a vehicle,
and is there to help the vehicle move more smoothly through the air.

mag-rocket.content: Rockets are used to propel vehicles.
They do this by burning fuel and forcing the exhaust out
a narrow opening in one of the ends of the rocket.

mag-sail.content: Sails are usually made of fabric.
They work by catching the wind and using it's force to do work,

mag-solar-panel.content: Solar panels are covered with light sensitive material.
This material converts sunlight into electricity,
which we can use or store in batteries.

mag-star.content: A star!  Try to find them hidden on every level.

mag-sunny-region.content: Sunlight can be captured and used as a source of heat and energy.

mag-tail-fin.content: Fins are added to vehicles to help control the direction of the vehicle.
Fins control how the air moves around it.

mag-tread.content: Treads are used to propel a vehicle across the ground.
Their large surface allows the tread to grip
the ground more easily so they don't slip.

mag-wheel-powered.content: Motors are engines that are attached to wheels
to rotate them and propel a vehicle.

mag-wheel.content: Wheels help us move across the ground more easily.
They are found in all kinds of things like bikes,

title-intro.content: Are you ready to earn your Rover Maker badge?
Rovers are vehicles we create to explore the surface of other planets.
To start making your own rovers,  press the green "play button."
If you want to revisit one of your old rovers, press Sunspot's tablet.
Or, to look at your badge collection, press the "badge button."

tutorial-again.content: Want to hear the tutorial again?
Press the orange square button, and it will replay the tutorial.

tutorial-basic-0.content: Your goal in each challenge is to create a rover
that will carry Sunspot to the finish line.
and if we build it right, it will end up here, with me, Sydney, at the finish line.

tutorial-basic-1.content: I went ahead and started this rover for you.
You just need to attach Sunspot's cockpit to the rest of the rover.
Tap and drag Sunspot's cockpit to move it.
Move the cockpit next to the other blocks and it will snap onto the rover.

tutorial-basic-2.content: When you're ready to try out your rover, press the "play button,"
and gravity will do the rest.
Don't worry if your rover doesn't work.
You can always press the "reset button" and try again.

unlock-moon.content: I think you're ready for a new challenge.
On the Moon, energy is hard to find,
so we'll learn how solar panels can help us recharge
our batteries, and keep our rover moving.
We'll also learn about rockets.  It's going to be fun!

tutorial-wind-0.content: Mars has dust storms that blow across the planet.
Let's see if we can design a rover that takes advantage of the wind to move.

tutorial-wind-1.content: With the sail, we can capture the wind and use it to push your rover.
I went ahead and attached one already.
Can you finish the rest of the rover and make it to the finish?

tutorial-wheels-1.content: When you've got the wheels in place,
press the "play button" to try it out.

tutorial-two-pieces-1.content: When you're happy with your rover, press the "play button" to try it out.

tutorial-two-pieces-0.content: This rover is missing some wheels and blocks.
Can you add them to complete the rover?
To attach blocks to the rover, drag and snap them
onto the side of other rover pieces.

tutorial-treads-2.content: Use these arrow buttons to control the treads.

tutorial-generic-1.content: Let's see what you can do!

tutorial-generic-2.content: What do you think is a good design for this course?

tutorial-generic-3.content: Hmm.. Do you think you can do it?

tutorial-generic-4.content: Oh boy!  Let's get to designing.

tutorial-holes.content: Uh oh.  There are big holes in the ground.
How can we design a rover to drive across them without falling in.

tutorial-basics-complete.content: This time it's up to you to design a rover to carry Sunspot to the finish.
You can use any of the pieces in the toolbox.
If you want to review the course, press the square button here to get a tour.

tutorial-generic-0.content: Ooh!  I can't wait to see what you come up with this time.

tutorial-moon.content: The Moon's gravity is weaker than Earth's.
The weaker gravity affects how your rover will move.
Let's build rovers and test them to see what will happen on the Moon.

tutorial-more-ice.content: This would be a good place for treads.

tutorial-motors-0.content: It looks like we'll be going uphill this time.
That means we'll need to use a wheel with a motor attached.

tutorial-rocket-0.content: Hmm... How are we supposed to get up this ledge?
Maybe we could use some of Jet's extra rockets on our rover.

tutorial-solar-1.content: I've added the battery and solar panel to your rover for you.

tutorial-solar-2.content: It looks like you need a solar panel to reach the goal.
Don't forget to add a battery, or you'll have nothing to charge.

tutorial-motors-1.content: In order to go uphill we need a wheel with a motor and batteries.
The battery will provide power for the motor,
and the motor will turn the wheel and move the rover.
I added the wheel and battery this time.  Can you finish the rest of the vehicle?

tutorial-motors-2-keyboard.content: Use these arrow buttons or the right and left arrows
on your keyboard to control the motor.
As you use the motor, your battery power will drain.
Don't take too long, or you'll run out of power and need to reset.

tutorial-motors-2.content: Use these arrow buttons to control the motor.
As you use the motor, your battery power will drain,
Don't take too long, or you'll run out of power and need to reset.

tutorial-motors-3.content: You'll need to use a wheel with a motor to get to the other end of this course.
Don't forget to add a battery to power the motor!
You can use more than one motorized wheel, or battery, if you want.
The more motors you add, the more power you'll need.
If you add more batteries, you'll have more power to use.

tutorial-no-treads.content: Hmm... I seem to have misplaced the treads.
We'll have to slide across the ice this time,
Make sure you get enough speed to get all the way across.

tutorial-rocket-1.content: Attach rockets to your rover and fly through the air!
I went ahead and attached one, but you can add more.
The more you add, the faster you'll go.
Just watch out that you don't lose control.

tutorial-rocket-2-keyboard.content: Hold the rocket button or the spacebar to fire your rockets.
Release the button, or spacebar to turn them off.
Rockets have limited fuel, so they'll only last so long.

tutorial-rocket-2.content: Hold the rocket button to fire your rockets.
Release the button to turn them off.
Rockets have limited fuel, so they'll only last so long.

tutorial-rocket-more.content: This looks like another good place to use rockets.
With rockets, you need to think about where you
place them, and how your rover is balanced.
Where you place your rockets will determine how
your rover moves and rotates when you fire them.

tutorial-solar-0.content: On the Moon, we can't just go to the store to pick up new batteries.
Solar panels can be used to charge up batteries.
You just need to get to a sunny spot like this,
for your panels to collect energy from the sun.
Finish this vehicle and let's head for the goal.

tutorial-star.content: Each level contains a sneaky star like this,
that you can collect by hitting it with your rover.
Sneaky stars are always in hard to reach places
You'll need to be a clever builder to get them all.

tutorial-treads-0.content: Europa is a small, cold moon of Jupiter,
and it's covered in ice, which makes it very slick.
Thankfully, I brought along some treads we can use to cross the ice.
Treads have better traction than tires.
That means they won't slip when we use them on ice.

tutorial-treads-1.content: I went ahead and attached some treads on your rover.
You'll need them to move across the ice, where a normal wheel would slip.
Treads need power to operate, so don't forget a battery.

tutorial-treads-2-keyboard.content: Use these arrow buttons, or the right and left arrows
on your keyboard, to control the treads.

tutorial-wheels-0.content: Can you help me add wheels to this rover?
Find the wheels in the toolbox on the left.
Tap a wheel and drag it out of the toolbox on top of the rover to attach it.
Wheels can attach anywhere on top of a rover.

tutorial-wind-2-keyboard.content: Hold the "sail button" or the z key to raise
your sails so the wind can push on it.
Release the button or key to lower your sail and slow down.
Lower your sail if you're going too fast,
or if the wind is about to tip your rover.

tutorial-wind-2.content: Hold the "sail button" to raise your sail so the wind can push on it.
Release the button to lower your sail and slow down.
Lower your sail if you're going too fast,
or if the wind is about to tip your rover.

tutorial-wind-sign.content: Whenever you see a sign like this, it means a dust storm is coming.
That means we can use the wind to move our rover.

unlock-earth.content: We'll start by building rovers on Earth before we head to another planet.
On Earth, we'll learn how to propel a rover using gravity and motors.

unlock-europa.content: You're getting really good at this!
Our final stop is on Europa.
Europa is really cold and covered in ice.
On Europa, we'll learn how to build a rover that can drive on slippery surfaces.

unlock-mars.content: On Mars, we'll learn about the power of wind,
and how that power can be used to move a rover.
